Introduction

The Road Accidents Data set contains over 250,000 observations from UK road accidents. The data in its raw form isnt clean and to practice proper data hygiene to avoid corrupted results, the data needs to be cleaned before creating visualisations. For this report, R will be used instead of Tableau as it provides more control over the data with its powerful tools.

R is a free and open source programming language for statistical computing and graphics, supported by the R Foundation. It is widely used among statisticians and data miners for developing statistical software and for data analysis. It has a vast array of libraries with powerful functions. R also has its own markdown language, R Mark-down (.rmd), which allows for creating documents explaining the process of data mining, cleaning, and creating visualisations with the results from running the R scripts. It supports the LaTeX format, which is used in the scientific community to create theses and publishable scientific papers.

This entire document is composed using the R Markdown language. Hence, all code used to clean, prepare and filter the data, along with the code for creating the visualisations are all included in this report. These code blocks can be recognised, as they are syntax highlighted. Hence, this report can be reproduced by running the R code blocks.

Any text output from running an R command will have a double hash prefix, for e.g.in R, the output from a print command to print Hello World! will be shown as follows: 

print("Hello World!")
## [1] "Hello World!"

The syntax highlighted statement is the R code, followed by its output on the next line with the double hash prefix. Please note, a single hash prefix is an inline comment.

For this report, the package will be used for data manipulation and the package will be used to create the data visualisations.

The package follows the ethos, where layers are used to bring visualisations to life. For e.g.following the ethos to generate a simple scatter plot, one would need to create an empty plot, with two axis, then add another layer which will contain the labels to the axis, followed by another layer, which contains the points for the data and another layer containing the line of best fit for the particular plot. Figure 1 shows the process of adding layers.

The Grammar of Graphics layers

Data Visualisations

Number of Accidents vs Sex of Driver vs Age of Driver

Motor-vehicle insurance companies often categorise men at a higher risk and age is also a factor that is taken into account. Are younger males more likely to be involved in a motor-vehicle accident compared to younger females? To answer this question, we need all male and female driver ages, which can be obtained by filtering the data through . But before we can proceed, lets look at all the unique values that are present in the sex_of_driver and age_of_driver variables: 

unique(data$sex_of_driver)
## [1]  1  2  3 -1

Now lets cross reference the code labels from the data description for sex_of_driver:

code label
1 Male
2 Female
3 Not known
-1 Data missing or out of range

So all observations with 3 and -1 are irrelevant and needs to be assigned as NA, which is a logical constant of length 1 that indicates a missing value in R. However, since we are only interested in the age of the driver, we can simply extract ages corresponding to male and females (1 & 2), which will omit all irrelevant values (3, -1).

Now lets check for negative and unusual data values in the age_of_driver variable, by obtaining its unique observations: 

unique(data$age_of_driver)
##  [1] 45 25 51 50 27 46 33 24 43 29 41 23 55 15 37 26 40 48 47 32 -1 31 30 13 34
## [26] 65 35 17 68 58 44 36 28 54 53 49 52 73 66 74 21 92 57 60 20 22 19 81 56 75
## [51]  9 18 38 42 10 14 69 62 72 59 70 87 61 71 64 67 39 77 79 63 76 80 78 11 16
## [76]  6 90 86 84 85  7 88 82 12 83 91  3 94  8 89  5 93  4  1 97 96

So there are negative values, -1, which needs to be filtered out. Lets extract male and female driver ages as separate vectors, remove -1 age value and finally, create a data frame with two columns, age and sex, the latter being populated with Male or Female depending on the sex of the variable. 

male_ages <- data %>% filter(sex_of_driver == 1) %>%
  select(age_of_driver)
male_ages <- male_ages[male_ages > 0] # Filter out -1.
# Turn into data frame.
male_ages <- data.frame(male_ages, rep("Male", length(male_ages)))
colnames(male_ages) <- c("age", "sex") # Assign column names.

female_ages <- data %>% filter(sex_of_driver == 2) %>%
  select(age_of_driver)
female_ages <- female_ages[female_ages > 0] # Filter out -1.
# Turn into data frame.
female_ages <- data.frame(female_ages, rep("Female", length(female_ages)))
colnames(female_ages) <- c("age", "sex") # Assign column names.

Now lets confirm the male and female observations doesnt contain -1: 

any(unique(male_ages$age)[unique(male_ages$age) == -1])
## [1] FALSE
any(unique(female_ages$age)[unique(female_ages$age) == -1])
## [1] FALSE

Now we can proceed to create a visualisation. The best way to visualise this information of age vs sex vs accidents is to create two separate histograms with respect to age, one for males, and one for females, and overlay the plots: 

# Combine male and female age data frame to a single data frame.
age_sex_df <- rbind(male_ages, female_ages)

require(wesanderson)
plot_age_sex <- ggplot(age_sex_df, aes(x = age, colour = sex, fill = sex)) + 
  labs(x = "Age of Driver", y = "No. of Accidents", colour = "Sex of Driver",
       fill = "Sex of Driver") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = wes_palette("GrandBudapest1")) +
  scale_color_manual(values = wes_palette("GrandBudapest1")) +
  geom_histogram(alpha=0.5, position = "identity") +
  theme_classic()

Lets also create another plot, where the day of the week is taken into account. Is there a particular day with more frequent accidents than others?

Lets look at all the unique values present in the day_of_week variable.

unique(data$day_of_week)
## [1] 2 7 4 6 5 1 3

The values needs to be substituted with the following code labels from the data description:

code label
1 Sunday
2 Monday
3 Tuesday
4 Wednesday
5 Thursday
6 Friday
7 Saturday

Substitute the values:

data$day_of_week[data$day_of_week == 1] <- "Sunday"
data$day_of_week[data$day_of_week == 2] <- "Monday"
data$day_of_week[data$day_of_week == 3] <- "Tuesday"
data$day_of_week[data$day_of_week == 4] <- "Wednesday"
data$day_of_week[data$day_of_week == 5] <- "Thursday"
data$day_of_week[data$day_of_week == 6] <- "Friday"
data$day_of_week[data$day_of_week == 7] <- "Saturday"

Create the weekday plot:

require(forcats)
require(wesanderson)
plot_days <- ggplot(data, aes(x = fct_rev(fct_infreq(day_of_week)),
                              fill = day_of_week)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(rev(wes_palette("GrandBudapest1")),
                               wes_palette("GrandBudapest1"))) +
  labs(y = "No. of Accidents", x = "Weekday") +
  geom_histogram(stat = "count") + 
  coord_flip() +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Now, is there a correlation with time?

times <- data %>% select(accident_index, time)

# Remove NA values
times <- na.omit(times)

plot_time <- ggplot(times, aes(x = time, fill = "lightcoral"))  +

Driver Sex vs Driver Age vs No.of Accidents vs Day vs Time

As you can see from Figure 2, there were more male driver accidents than female driver accidents, where younger drivers make up for the majority of the accidents irrespective of sex. But, it is important to know that the conclusion from the visualisation doesnt take how many male and female drivers there are in the UK. So if there are more male drivers than female drivers, statistically speaking, a higher proportion of accidents can be linked to male drivers.

Geo-spatial plot of accidents

Are accidents more likely to occur in densely populated areas such as city centres? To answer this question, a Geo-spatial plot is required, with a density heat-map using the longitude and latitude data.

But before we can proceed, we need to clean the data. Since longitude and latitude data is likely to have large amounts of variation, it is futile to try and obtain unique values and look for outliers. However, has built in pattern recognition for this case, which will automatically omit evident outliers.

library(maps)
library(mapproj)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(ggrepel)

UK <- map_data("world", "UK") # Obtain UK map.
UK_cities <- world.cities %>% filter(country.etc == "UK")

plot_geo_uk <- ggplot(data = UK, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group)) + 
  geom_polygon(fill = "azure2") +
  coord_map() +
  theme_void() +
  geom_point(aes(longitude, latitude), data = data, col = "deepskyblue3",
             alpha = 0.025, size = 1e-1, inherit.aes = FALSE) +
  
  
  # For the density heatmap:
  stat_density2d(aes(longitude, latitude, fill = ..level..),
                 data = data,
                 geom = "polygon",
             inherit.aes = FALSE) +
  labs(fill = "Accident Density") +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colours = rev(brewer.pal(7, "Spectral"))) + 
  
  
  # Retrieve top 9 UK Cities, sorted by population density,
  # and add them as labels.
  geom_label_repel(data=UK_cities %>% arrange(pop) %>%
                     tail(9), aes(x=long, y=lat, label=name),
                     size=5, inherit.aes = FALSE, box.padding = 2.1,
                   max.iter = 50000, nudge_y = 1.25, nudge_x = 0.15) +
  geom_point( data=UK_cities%>% arrange(pop) %>% 
                    tail(9), aes(x=long, y=lat), color="black",
                    size=1, inherit.aes = FALSE)

Geospatial plot of accidents

Looking at the data, we can easily see that major UK cities have more accidents than the UK countryside, this can be due to the areas being densely populated, which means more vehicles and people, which in-turn increases the risk of an accident.
